Chapter: The Effects of Urbanization in Wake County
Description: Wake County is one of the fastest-growing regions in the United States. Estimates say that about 56 people move to Wake County each day. Technological, educational, and industrial benefits all are huge draws for the area.

Before European colonization, the Raleigh area was home to indigenous tribes including the Tuscarora and Occaneechi. Sir Walter Raleigh, among others, funded a group of colonists to establish the Cittie of Raleigh. These colonists landed on Roanoke Island in 1587 and later became known as the "Lost Colony" after the settlement was found abandonded in 1591. In 1771 the General Assembly created Wake County. In 1792, Raleigh was founded as the state capital of North Carolina.
